Slice it horizontally. Then we can describe it in the following way. For fixed $x$, we can integrate $y$ from $y=\frac{2x}{\pi}$ to $y=\sin x$. Then we integrate $x$ from $0$ to the point $P$ where $P$ is the intersection of $y=\sin x$ and $y=\frac{2x}{\pi}$. Since $P$ is $(\frac{\pi}{2},1)$ by solving the equation \[y=\sin x,\quad\text{and}\quad y=\frac{2x}{\pi},\]
the region is described by $\frac{2x}{\pi}\leq y\leq \sin x$ and $0\leq x\leq \frac{\pi}{2}$. Then the iterated integral should be
\[\iint_D2y\,dA=\int_0^{\pi/2}\int_{2x/\pi}^{\sin x}2y\,dy\,dx.\]
Evaluate: 
\[\begin{split}
  \int_0^{\pi/2}\int_{2x/\pi}^{\sin x}2y\,dy\,dx&=\int_0^{\pi/2}\left.\left(y^2\right)\right\rvert_{2x/\pi}^{\sin x}\,dx=\int_0^{\pi/2}\left(\sin^2x-\left(\frac{2x}{\pi}\right)^2\right)\,dx\\
  &=\left.\left(\frac{1}{2}x-\frac{\sin 2x}{4}-\frac{4}{\pi^2}\frac{x^3}{3}\right)\right\rvert_0^{\pi/2}=1-\frac{\pi}{12}.
\end{split}\]
