The region is $0\leq v\leq 1-u$, and $0\leq u\leq 1$. Then we let $(u=0,v=0)$ map to $(x=1,y=1,z=0)$, $(u=1,v=0)$ map to $(x=2,y=1,z=2)$ and $(u=0,v=1)$ map to $(x=2,y=3,z=3)$. Since all lines are straight, we may assume $x=au+bv+c$, $y=du+ev+f$, $z=gu+hv+i$. Then we have equations
\begin{align*}
    1=0a+0b+c,&\quad 2=1a+0b+c,\quad 2=0a+1b+c,\\
    1=0d+0e+f,&\quad 1=1d+0e+f,\quad 3=0d+1e+f,\\
    0=0g+0h+i,&\quad 2=1g+0h+i,\quad 3=0g+1h+i.
\end{align*}
The solution is 
\begin{align*}
    a=1,&\quad b=1,\quad c=1,\\
    d=0,&\quad e=2,\quad f=1,\\
    g=2,&\quad h=3,\quad i=0,\\
\end{align*}
Therefore the parametrization is
\[x=u+v+1,\quad y=2v+1,\quad z=2u+3v,\quad \text{for }0\leq v\leq 1-u,\ 0\leq u\leq 1.\]
Then \[\textbf{T}_u=(1,0,2),\quad \textbf{T}_v=(1,2,3).\]
Then \[\begin{split}
    \textbf{n}=\textbf{T}_u\times \textbf{T}_v=&-4\textbf{i}-\textbf{j}+2\textbf{k}=(-4,-1,2).
\end{split}\]
Therefore \[\norm{\textbf{n}}=\norm{\textbf{T}_u\times \textbf{T}_v}=\sqrt{(-4)^2+(-1)^2+e^2}=\sqrt{21}.\]
Hence\[A(S)=\int_0^{1}\int_0^{1-u}\sqrt{21}\,dv\,du=\frac{21}{2}.\]

